{"questionId":"2812750","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>BA</mi><mo>]</mo></math> is extended to form an isosceles triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DAC</mi></math>, with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mi>θ</mi></math>, as shown in the following diagram.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/7c4930c9e06a14d93ccad02443cf647cf5c8611c.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mtext>C</mtext><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1 (using supplementary angles)</strong></p>\n<p>recognizing <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> are supplementary&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>recognizing supplementary angles have the same sine value&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn><mi>θ</mi></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>9</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2 (using sine rule)</strong></p>\n<p>recognizing <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CD</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mtext>C</mtext><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>b</mi><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>correct substitution of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mfrac><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>a</mi></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math> into sine rule &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mfenced><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>a</mi></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfenced><mfenced><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfenced></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi><mfenced><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfenced></mrow><mfenced><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>a</mi></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfenced></mfrac></math> &nbsp;</strong>(or equivalent)</p>\n<p><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>9</mn></mfrac></math> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong><em>[3 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"2812750","referenceCode":"23M.1.SL.TZ2.8c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the value of sin CA^D.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.5—Unit circle definitions of sin, cos, tan. Exact trig ratios, ambiguous case of sine rule"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}